# Rust code smells

Anti-patterns this project refactors against. Each entry: the smell,
why it hurts, the cure.

## `unwrap()` / `expect()` in production paths

**Smell.** `let x = foo().unwrap();` in a library or service path.

**Why.** A `Result::Err` or `Option::None` becomes a process-killing
panic. Any caller invariant you imagined isn't enforced.

**Cure.** `?` to propagate, `match` to handle. `expect("…")` is
acceptable only when the invariant *cannot* be violated and you can
explain why in the message. Tests and `main()` can `unwrap`; production
code paths cannot.

## `.clone()` to silence the borrow checker

**Smell.** A `.clone()` on every reference because reasoning about
lifetimes felt hard.

**Why.** Each clone is a real copy. Hot paths suffer. The clone often
hides a design problem the borrow checker was actually pointing at.

**Cure.** Borrow (`&T`). Restructure (move the data into the function
once). Use `Cow`. Only clone when the cost is acceptable *and* you
know it's a copy.

## Primitive obsession

**Smell.** `fn charge(user_id: u64, amount: u32, currency: String)`.

**Why.** Argument-order bugs become silent. Domain validation is at
every call site. The type checker can't help.

**Cure.** Newtypes (`UserId`, `Money`, `Currency`). See `patterns.md`.

## Stringly-typed APIs

**Smell.** `fn set_status(status: &str)` accepting `"pending"`,
`"paid"`, `"refunded"`.

**Why.** Typos go to runtime. Adding a status doesn't update call
sites. Exhaustive matching is impossible.

**Cure.** An `enum Status { Pending, Paid, Refunded }`. The compiler
now checks every site.

## `Box<dyn Trait>` when generics would do

**Smell.** `fn render(r: Box<dyn Renderer>)` in a place where one
concrete renderer is passed.

**Why.** Dynamic dispatch, heap allocation, lost monomorphisation
optimisations, optional vtable indirection.

**Cure.** `fn render<R: Renderer>(r: R)` or `fn render(r: impl
Renderer)`. Reserve `dyn` for true heterogeneity (a list of mixed
implementers).

## `Rc<RefCell<T>>` in the domain layer

**Smell.** Shared mutable state inside `src/domain/`.

**Why.** Interior mutability defeats the borrow checker's analysis;
runtime borrow panics become possible; the design has hidden coupling.

**Cure.** Pass references through. Use an owning struct that exposes
`&mut` to one caller at a time. If you genuinely need shared mutable
state, lift it to `application/` or `infrastructure/`.

## `Vec` parameters

**Smell.** `fn sum(items: Vec<u32>)`.

**Why.** Forces the caller to allocate or move. `&[u32]` works just as
well and is strictly more flexible.

**Cure.** `fn sum(items: &[u32])`. Same for `String` → `&str` in
parameters.

## Wide `match` arms with `_ => {}` swallowing variants

**Smell.** A `match` over an enum with `_ => {}` as the last arm to
"handle the rest".

**Why.** Adding a new variant won't trigger an exhaustiveness error.
The new variant is silently dropped.

**Cure.** Match every variant explicitly. Add a final `// no-op for X
and Y` rather than `_`. When you genuinely need a catch-all, name the
arms and add `#[non_exhaustive]` on your enum upstream.

## Re-deriving when a method exists

**Smell.** `impl Debug for Foo { fn fmt(...) ... }` that exactly
matches what `#[derive(Debug)]` would produce.

**Why.** Maintenance burden, drift from upstream behaviour.

**Cure.** Derive when possible. Hand-roll only when you need custom
formatting (e.g. redacting secrets).

## Generic-soup signatures

**Smell.** `fn foo<A: B + C + D, E: F<G = H>, I, J>(a: A, e: E, ...)`.

**Why.** Unreadable. Hard to call. Compile times bloom.

**Cure.** Extract trait aliases (when stable: `trait Logger = Display
+ Sync + Send;`). Use named lifetimes. Split the function. Group
related parameters into a struct.

## Naming things `Manager`, `Helper`, `Service` with no further specifics

**Smell.** `struct UserManager`, `impl UserManager { fn get_user, fn
create_user, fn update_user, fn delete_user }`.

**Why.** "Manager" describes everything and nothing. Such structs
attract responsibilities until they're God Objects.

**Cure.** Split into focused types named for what they actually own —
`UserRepository`, `UserAuthenticator`, `UserDtoMapper`. (DDD
vocabulary; see `general/ddd.md`.)

## Mixing async colours

**Smell.** An async function that internally blocks (`std::fs::read`,
`std::thread::sleep`, sync database call).

**Why.** Blocks the runtime's executor thread; can deadlock multi-task
workloads.

**Cure.** Use the async equivalent (`tokio::fs::read`,
`tokio::time::sleep`). For unavoidable sync work,
`tokio::task::spawn_blocking`.

## Unsafe without a `SAFETY:` comment

**Smell.** `unsafe { … }` with no comment, or a comment that says
"this is fine".

**Why.** The reviewer cannot tell whether the invariants hold. The
next refactor may break them silently.

**Cure.** Every `unsafe` block has a `// SAFETY:` comment listing the
caller-side invariants. The pair *(unsafe code, safety comment)* is
the audit unit.

## "It compiles" as the bar

**Smell.** Code that compiles, clippy is silenced with `#[allow(...)]`
sprinkled on top, and a test happens to pass.

**Why.** Future readers don't know what the silences mean. The
silences accumulate. The codebase rots.

**Cure.** Each `#[allow(...)]` is on a single item with a comment
explaining *why* the lint is wrong for that specific case. Crate-wide
`#![allow(...)]` is forbidden.

## Re-implementing the standard library

**Smell.** Hand-rolled `iter()` adapters. Manual binary search. Custom
ordered map.

**Why.** Slower, buggier, harder to read.

**Cure.** `std::collections`, `std::iter`, `std::cmp`. Search before
implementing.
